A ship of one Thomas Keyser and one James Smith,

1645 
 the latter a member of the church of Boston, first

Chap. V.} brought upon the colonies the guilt of participating in the traffic in African slaves.

They sailed for Guinea to trade for negroes;



Winthrop, II. 243, 244, 245. but throughout Massachusetts the cry of justice was raised against them as malefactors and murderers; Richard Saltonstall, a worthy assistant, felt himself moved by his duty as a magistrate, to denounce the act of stealing negroes as expressly contrary to the law of God and the law of the country;



Ibid. II. 379, 380. the guilty men were committed for the offence;



Colony Records, III. 45. and, after advice with the elders, the representatives of the people, bearing witness against the

1646. heinous crime of man-stealing, ordered the negroes to be restored, at the public charge, to their native country, with a letter expressing the indignation of the general court at their wrongs.



Colony Laws, c. XII

The settlement of New England was a result of

Chap VIII.} the Reformation;



Heeren, i. 102, 103 not of the contest between the new opinions and the authority of Rome, but of implacable differences between Protestant dissenters and the established Anglican church.
